.TH _printf 3 "April 2026" "_printf man-page"

.SH NAME
_printf - formatted output

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include  <main.h>
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *format, ...);"

.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB_printf()\fP function produces output according to a format string and writes the result to stdout (standard output stream).

The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not %), which are copied unchanged to the output, and conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching the corresponding argument.

Each conversion specification is introduced by the character \fB%\fP and ends with a conversion specifier.

The \fB_printf()\fP function does not handle flag characters, field width, precision, or length modifiers.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B c
Prints a single character. The int argument is converted to an unsigned char.

.TP
.B s
Prints a string of characters. If the argument is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B d, i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B u
Prints an unsigned decimal integer.

.TP
.B o
Prints an unsigned octal integer.

.TP
.B x
Prints an unsigned hexadecimal integer (lowercase).

.TP
.B X
Prints an unsigned hexadecimal integer (uppercase).

.TP
.B b
Prints an unsigned integer in binary notation (custom specifier).

.TP
.B %
Prints a literal '%' character.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon success, \fB_printf()\fP returns the number of characters printed, excluding the terminating null byte.

If the format string is NULL or ends with an incomplete conversion specifier, -1 is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
_printf("Hello, World!\n");
.PP
Output: Hello, World!

.PP
_printf("Number: %d\n", 42);
.PP
Output: Number: 42

.PP
_printf("Hex: %x\n", 255);
.PP
Output: ff

.PP
_printf("Binary: %b\n", 98);
.PP
Output: 1100010

